Driving is not cheap. Fuel prices have risen sharply since the beginning of the year and could get worse. Government implemented relief on fuel levies, but that comes to an end this month. Many are now calling for an extension. Economist Dawie Roodt has more. #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Customers could soon be paying R25 for a litre of petrol, that's the cautionary note coming from economist Dawie Roodt. For the past two month's government has provided relief by reducing fuel levies but that comes to an end this month. READ: Cosatu calls for govt to extend fuel levy reduction While some are asking for an extension, Roodt says government is looking at other options. He said, "the Minister gave us a reduction of R1.50 for two months and that's coming to an end and if you add that. Then I'm afraid we are talking about  a petrol price in the region of  R4.00 a litre which will push up the price to about R25.00. This is the biggest increase ever. The Minister did mention that we could de-regulate the petrol price that would mean retailers can set their own price. But the disadvantage would be no profits. On the other hand urban areas it would make the price cheaper but in less populated areas it wouldn't help much. But truthfully there isn't much that we can do, the rand is weak a